•	Their main objective is to poach employees from other manufacturers around the country.
•	Barriers to employment are (HIGH COST OF HOUSING) the rent prices are sky high, landlords wont rent unless you have a 700-credit score, every time you apply it hurts your credit school, so it is a vicious cycle.  (NO ACCESS TO CHILDCARE) Kent County receives less than new castle in compensation for childcare services.  This leads there to be fewer childcare operators since they cannot sustain a business in Kent County.  (Transportation) there is no bus route to or near the factory period.  At least 10 employees apparently walk to work or must use uber to get to work from Dover.  The facility is only 2 miles outside of the city.
•	They have over 150 applicants a month.  Finding people to apply isn’t hard its keeping them and having them stay due to the 3 major issues listed above.  
•	Contacted and left a VM for DART

notes_general:
Very extensive and detailed converstaion about the current crisis facing the Delawre childcare industry...

Has been in extensive contact with the DOL.  
"DJL does not work and is uselses"
Doesn't seem to be able to use WOTC or any other DOL program successfully
-cannot qualify for Elevate DE since they have 3 seperate centers totally over 100 employees

Thinks that the wellfare system is what is causing the low end labor shortage... People get paid to stay at home and now work jobs like these.  The state needs to ensentive people to work not, not to work.  

- The industry is in a labor crisis.  There are no CDA certified candidates in the market place.  Once this becomes the standard it will greatly impact the number of people they can recruite from.  Previous TECE 1/2 canidates will not longer be able to teach in centers and have to go back for re-education. Doing this at a time when these centers can't find employees is counter productive.  

-Wants people with education degrees to be able to work/teach in Childcare Centers without CDA or TECE 1/2

- Wants the state to provide a tax credit to SIC W2 employees who work in the Childcare/ ECE field.  

- Has great disapointement with DOE employees office of early learning, john kline and kaley gleenson.

"no consequences for not working"
"entitlement programs are hurting the industry"

in order to pay what the teachers deserve the childcare facility will need to charge 500-600 a week per child as opposed to 200-300.  That is the only way wages can go up to what they need to be in intise people to work in this field.  The state hasn't raised their rates since 2021 and clearly everything has increased in cost since. Rent, labor, diapers, food, gas, insurance, etc.  Charging the same prices cannot continue.  I am going to refer this to Joanna and see what we can do.

notes_general:
Ongoing need for speech therapist, OTs & PTs; multiple of each; $38-45/hr + bonuses for productivity for the clinicians 
21 people -- mostly therapists with MAs; a couple admins and a couple therapist assistant positions as well; 
assitants help with materials, cleaning, visual support; most of the time is people with bachelors, or in college for OT -- sort of internships 
had people for observation, sometimes hire under 18 for front desk; would love for more kids to learn -- interersted in DOWBL 

have tried to get connected to UD for speech therapy -- have attempted to work with them but haven't heard back. do have an agreement with DelTech for COTA program -- doesn't start until 2024; have taken student interns from DelState; internships have come more from online programs 

huge need for all therapies & allied health; constantly have an open position for speech; she can't find a PT right now; had more luck with OT; overall, therapies are an underrepresented population & there's a huge need in all settings; not even a speech program in Delaware until recently; from other practice owners & online -- pay is not to the level it should be for the degree of schooling -- insurance reimbursement for private practice isn't enough; big burnout in the field because of demand and case load -- can have 80-100 children in schools at a time; can't hire in person within Capital School District because people all want to telework 

programs are also really exclusive and small -- only about 25 clinicians a year graduating, which doesn't keep up with people are retiring or moving out of the field; not necessarily an aging workforce, but just small programs generally; growing at same rate as it always has, but the level of need is so much greater because kids are requiring more services now than ever before -- can't keep up with need without increased entrance into the workforce -- need a masters

notes_general:
Called me back after a VM nice guy

Has one open position constantly looking for a project manager (75k) hiring and firing them due to poor preformance.

Needs someone to show up on time with a clean driving record to run materials to job sites ($18-20hr)

Completely unaware of DJL and Elevate DE or any services (told him about them) however he did not want to share his email address or be connected to any other departments.

Info from contact: (OOO for surgery, so sent info in email)

"Having said that, the automotive industry overall needs qualified technicians.  There are little new entries into this profession yet a large number of those exiting the profession.  90+% of Delaware automotive repair facilities are in search of qualified employees.   I am one of those.  I do not have the answers, but it is a growing problem.  I have been searching for over two years with no success.

 

There is an area the State can help.  If we hire someone with little experience and it doesn’t work out, the business suffers with unemployment claims issues and subsequent higher rates from the State.  I would urge passing of laws that allows us to hire on a temporary basis (90 days) without penalty should the employee not be suited for the profession.  I could grow if I could find employees."

notes_general:
Business has 4 locations: 2 in Laurel, 1 in Seaford, 1 in Lakewood - all have their own childcare and business licenses, and different names, but insurance and federal taxes are the same 
Everyone is an employee of Sussex Preschools - 50-55 employees - need close to 70 to be fully staffed 
Having issues hiring for the past 4-5 years, which was exasperated by Covid 
Finding teachers is hard - once they get certified, school districts scout and teachers can go to a school district with GED, get state benefits, and summers off, no weekends etc. 

Have their own professional development cohort for CDA - for council that oversees CDA cert, can do 120 hours across 8 topics - many online classes available but not a lot of in person options

only scholarship available is extremely limited & only covers online --> Elevate Delaware -- have not had anyone successfully apply; waivering right at the employee mark; colleagues in childcare industry with under 50 employees have tried and were also rejected for unknown reasons

asked about childcare appenticeship program --> will get back to her about this question
